jk",",,, Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","<,,, Wales>":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1230–":"about 1230–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1247–1335":"1247–1335","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1265–1305":"1265–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1196–1290":"1196–1290","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","Abt 1230":"about 1230","1305":"1305","<1259>":"1259","1335":"1335","1247":"1247","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1196":"1196","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Gloddaith, Eglwys Rhos, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom",",,, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","<,,, Wales>":"Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Iorwerth ap Madog was born about 1230, in Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Iorworth ap Gwarin, was 35 and his mother, Joyce Ferch Hywel, was 22. He married Gwerfyl verch Cynwrig in 1259, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1230–":"umbes 1230–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1247–1335":"1247–1335","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1265–1305":"1265–1305","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1196–1290":"1196–1290","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","1305":"1305","<1259>":"1259","1335":"1335","1247":"1247","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1196":"1196","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Gloddaith, Eglwys Rhos, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Gloddaith, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom",",,, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","<,,, Wales>":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1230–":"noin 1230–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1247–1335":"1247–1